this is exactly the kind of faith that Christ talks about.  Faith as trust.  God does not want &quot;belief&quot; in him.  He wants our hearts and trust in him.

For instance, when Jesus says, &quot;Oh ye of little faith,&quot; the greek word [i:1coqr6za]ojligopistiva[/i:1coqr6za] is being used, which means &quot;trusting to little&quot;
Also, the greek word [i:1coqr6za]pivstiÃ¯[/i:1coqr6za] is often used, which means, &quot;conviction of the truth of anything, generally with trust,&quot; or &quot;belief with the predominate idea of trust&quot;

God never uses the word faith to mean, &quot;believe in something that has no evidence of being true&quot; nor does he equate our relationship with God with &quot;believing in his existence.&quot;


To drive the point even further, James also talks about in his book, [i:1coqr6za]&quot;Do you still think it's enough just to believe that there is one God? Well, even the demons believe this, and they tremble in terror!&quot;[/i:1coqr6za]
- James 2:19

pretty neat stuff.
